entries.meaning: Alternative form of jheel (“wetland area in India”)
examples: The pieces of stagnant water may be divided into jeels which contain water throughout the year, and chaongre which dry up in the cold season.

description: Manx jeeyl, jeeill ("damage"), cognate to Irish díobháil.

examples: And the gel, you know, as freckened as freckened,
Because of coorse she navar reckoned
But Misthriss Banks could do the jeel 1
She was braggin she could, and she'd take and kneel
On her bended knees, and she'd cuss — the baste !
